Scotland and [[England national football team|England]] are the oldest national football teams in the world.<ref name="oldest">{{cite web | last=Mitchell | first=Paul | title=The first international football match | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0012/ | publisher=BBC | access-date=12 September 2013 | archive-date=14 August 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814212110/http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0012/ | url-status=live }}</ref> Teams representing the two sides first competed at [[the Oval]] in [[England v Scotland representative football matches (1870–72)|five matches]] between 1870 and 1872. The two countries contested [[1872 Scotland v England football match|the first official international football match]], at [[Hamilton Crescent]] in [[Partick]], Scotland, on 30 November 1872. The match ended in a goalless draw.<ref name="oldest"/> All eleven players who represented Scotland that day played for [[Glasgow]] amateur club [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]].<ref name="oldest" /> Over the next forty years, Scotland played matches exclusively against the other three [[Home Nations]]—England, [[Wales national football team|Wales]] and [[Ireland national football team (1882–1950)|Ireland]]. The [[British Home Championship]] began in 1883, making these games competitive. The encounters against England were particularly fierce and a [[England–Scotland football rivalry|rivalry]] quickly developed.<ref name="them"/>

Scotland lost just two of their first 43 international matches. It was not until a 2–0 home defeat by Ireland in 1903 that Scotland lost a match to a team other than England. This run of success meant that Scotland would have regularly topped the [[World Football Elo Ratings|Elo ratings]], which were calculated in 1998, between 1876 and 1904. Scotland won the British Home Championship outright on 24 occasions, and shared the title 17 times with at least one other team.<ref group="note">The competition used neither goal difference nor goal average to separate teams level on points, so the title was shared instead.</ref><ref name="britchamp">{{cite web | title=British Home Championship Overview | url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesb/bhc.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | access-date=14 May 2007 | archive-date=31 December 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111231224555/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc.html | url-status=live }}</ref> A noteworthy victory for Scotland before the [[Second World War]] was the 5–1 victory over England in 1928, which led to that Scotland side being known as the "[[Wembley Wizards]]". Scotland played their first match outside the British Isles in 1929, beating [[Norway national football team|Norway]] 7–3 in [[Bergen, Norway|Bergen]].<ref name="euroresults">{{cite web | title=Scotland&nbsp;– International Matches 1921–1930 | url=https://www.rsssf.org/tabless/scot-intres1930.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | access-date=15 May 2007 | archive-date=11 May 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511111038/http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scot-intres1930.html | url-status=live }}</ref> Scotland continued to contest regular [[exhibition game|friendly matches]] against European opposition and enjoyed wins against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] and [[France national football team|France]] before losing to the [[Austria national football team|Austrian]] "[[Wunderteam]]" and [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in 1931.<ref name="euroresults" />

Scotland, like the other Home Nations, did not enter the three [[FIFA World Cup]]s held during the 1930s. This was because the four associations had been excluded from [[FIFA]] due to a disagreement regarding the status of amateur players.<ref name = "fifa">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/bodies/congress/britishassociation.html |title=The four British associations return to FIFA after the Second World War: 25th FIFA Congress in Luxembourg in 1946 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614215341/http://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/bodies/congress/britishassociation.html |archive-date=14 June 2010|publisher=FIFA |access-date=20 February 2010}}</ref> The four associations, including Scotland, returned to the FIFA fold after the Second World War.<ref name = "fifa"/> A match between a [[United Kingdom national football team|United Kingdom team]] and a [[World XI|"Rest of the World" team]] was played at [[Hampden Park]] in 1947 to celebrate this reconciliation.<ref name = "fifa"/>

===1950s: Entering the World Cup===
[[File:Matt Busby 1957.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[Matt Busby]] was due to manage Scotland at the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]], but was unable due to his injuries from the [[Munich air disaster]].]]
The readmission of the [[Scottish Football Association]] to FIFA meant that Scotland were eligible to enter the [[1950 FIFA World Cup]]. FIFA advised that places would be awarded to the top two teams in the [[1949&ndash;50 British Home Championship|British Home Championship]], but the SFA announced that Scotland would only attend the finals if Scotland won that competition. Scotland won their first two matches, but a 1–0 home defeat by [[England national football team|England]] meant that the Scots finished as runners-up. Scotland had qualified by right for the World Cup, but had not met the demand of the SFA to win the Championship. The SFA stood by this proclamation, despite pleas to the contrary by the Scotland players, supported by England captain [[Billy Wright (footballer, born 1924)|Billy Wright]] and the other England players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0001/print.shtml|title=BBC – A Sporting Nation – Scotland and the 1950 World Cup|publisher=BBC|access-date=25 December 2019|archive-date=30 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220530134422/https://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0001/print.shtml|url-status=live}}</ref> The SFA instead sent the team on a tour of North America.<ref>"The Queens" by Iain McCartney on Creedon Publications, 2004</ref>

The same qualification rules were in place for the [[1954 FIFA World Cup]], and Scotland finished second in the [[1953&ndash;54 British Home Championship|British Home Championship]]. This time the SFA allowed the team to participate in the World Cup, but its "preparation was atrocious".<ref name="scottishfa.co.uk">{{cite web |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=399&colour=home |website=scottishfa.co.uk |publisher=Scottish Football Association |title=Founding Fathers Humbled |access-date=27 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212024531/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=399&colour=home |archive-date=12 December 2008}}</ref> The SFA only sent 13 players to the finals, even though FIFA allowed 22-man squads.<ref name = "secret weapon"/> Despite this self-imposed hardship in terms of players, SFA dignitaries travelled in numbers, accompanied by their wives.<ref name = "secret weapon">{{cite news |last=Murphy |first=Alex |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/scotland/article1878706.ece |title=Docherty: spirit is Scotland's secret weapon |newspaper=The Times |date=4 June 2007 |access-date=6 November 2008 |archive-date=29 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429084420/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/scotland/article1878706.ece |url-status=dead }}</ref> Scotland lost 1–0 against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in their first game in the finals, which prompted the team [[Manager (association football)|manager]] [[Andy Beattie]] to resign hours before the game against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]].<ref>Andrew Ward, "Scotland: The Team" (The Breedon Book Publishing Company Limited, Derby, 1987), page 60.</ref> Uruguay were reigning champions and had never before lost a game at the World Cup finals, and they defeated Scotland 7–0.<ref name="scottishfa.co.uk"/><ref>{{cite web | title=World Cup 1954 finals | url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/54full.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | access-date=17 September 2008 | archive-date=6 March 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306144940/http://rsssf.com/tables/54full.html | url-status=live }}</ref>

The [[1958 FIFA World Cup]] finals saw Scotland draw their first game against [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]] 1–1, but they then lost to [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]] and [[France national football team|France]] and went out at the first stage.<ref name = "wsc 1958">{{cite news |url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/919-World-Cup/6145-law-of-averages |first=Chris |last=Freddi |title=Law of averages |newspaper=When Saturday Comes |date=June 1998 |access-date=14 October 2015 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000439/http://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/919-World-Cup/6145-law-of-averages |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Matt Busby]] had been due to manage the team at the World Cup, but the severe injuries he suffered in the [[Munich air disaster]] meant that trainer [[Dawson Walker]] took charge of the team instead.<ref name = "wsc 1958"/>

===1960s: Ian McColl and Home Championship successes===
Under the management of [[Ian McColl]], Scotland enjoyed consecutive British Home Championship successes in [[1961–62 British Home Championship|1962]] and [[1962–63 British Home Championship|1963]].<ref name="britchamp" /> [[Jock Stein]], [[John Prentice (footballer, born 1926)|John Prentice]] and [[Malky MacDonald]] all had brief spells as manager before [[Bobby Brown (footballer, born 1923)|Bobby Brown]] was appointed in 1967.<ref name="managers">{{cite web | title=Scotland Manager Records | url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/man/aamanagers.html | website=londonhearts.com | publisher=London Hearts Supporters' Club | access-date=27 September 2013 | archive-date=3 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003031659/http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/man/aamanagers.html | url-status=live }}</ref> Brown's first match as manager was against the [[1966 FIFA World Cup|newly crowned world champions]] England at Wembley Stadium. Despite being underdogs, Scotland won 3–2 thanks to goals from [[Denis Law]], [[Bobby Lennox]] and [[Jim McCalliog]].<ref name="wizards">{{cite web | title=Wembley Wizards 1967 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0022/page03.shtml | publisher=BBC | access-date=15 May 2007 | archive-date=15 May 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515081934/http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0022/page03.shtml | url-status=live }}</ref> Having defeated the world champions on their own turf, the Scotland fans hailed their team as the "[[Unofficial Football World Championships|unofficial world champions]]".<ref>{{cite book | author=Paul Brown | title=The Unofficial Football World Championships | publisher=Tonto Sport |year=2006 | isbn=0-9552183-1-4}}</ref> Despite this famous win, the Scots failed to qualify for any major competitions during the 1960s.<ref name = "wsc 1958"/>

===1970s: World Cups and Ally MacLeod===

[[File:Selección Escocesa 1972.jpg|thumb|left|The national football team of Scotland in 1972]]

After [[Tommy Docherty]]'s brief spell as manager, [[Willie Ormond]] was hired in 1973.<ref name="managers" /> Ormond lost his first match in charge 5–0 to England, but recovered to steer Scotland to their first World Cup finals in 16 years in 1974. At the [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974 World Cup]] finals in [[West Germany]], Scotland achieved their most impressive performance at a World Cup tournament.<ref name = "1974 best">{{cite news |last=Hepburn |first=Ray |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |date=21 March 2010 |access-date=28 July 2010 |url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/columnists/ray-hepburn/Why-the-Scotland-1974-World-Cup-side-gets-my-vote-as-best-ever-The-Ray-Hepburn-Column-article362351.html |title=Why the Scotland 1974 World Cup side gets my vote as best ever |archive-date=12 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012060953/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/columnists/ray-hepburn/Why-the-Scotland-1974-World-Cup-side-gets-my-vote-as-best-ever-The-Ray-Hepburn-Column-article362351.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The team was unbeaten but failed to progress beyond the group stages on [[goal difference]].<ref name = "1974 best"/> After beating [[DR Congo national football team|Zaïre]], they drew with both [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]], and went out because they had beaten Zaïre by the smallest margin.<ref name="brazil74" />

Scotland appointed [[Ally MacLeod]] as manager in 1977, with qualification for the [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978 World Cup]] in [[Argentina]] far from assured.<ref name="managers" /> The team made a strong start under MacLeod by winning the [[1977 British Home Championship]], largely thanks to a 2–1 victory over England at Wembley.<ref name="britchamp" /> The [[Tartan Army|Scotland fans]] invaded the pitch after the match, ripping up the turf and breaking a crossbar.<ref>{{cite news | title=Scots stash souvenirs under Wembley | url=http://news.scotsman.com/weirdoddandquirkystories/Scots-stash-souvenirs-under-Wembley.3359192.jp | newspaper=The Scotsman | date=1 April 2007 | access-date=21 September 2008 | location=Edinburgh | first=Nicholas | last=Christian | archive-date=10 January 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110060033/http://news.scotsman.com/weirdoddandquirkystories/Scots-stash-souvenirs-under-Wembley.3359192.jp | url-status=live }}</ref> Scotland's form continued as they secured qualification for the World Cup with victories over [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[Wales national football team|Wales]].<ref name="rsssf.com">{{cite web | title=Scotland&nbsp;– International Matches 1976–1980 | url=https://www.rsssf.org/tabless/scot-intres1980.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | access-date=15 May 2007 | archive-date=11 May 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511110957/http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scot-intres1980.html | url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-N0614-0028, Fußball-WM, Zaire - Schottland 0-2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Billy Bremner]] (right) playing for Scotland against [[Zaire national football team|Zaire]] at the [[Westfalenstadion]] in the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]]]]

During the build-up to the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]], MacLeod fuelled the hopes of the nation by stating that Scotland would come home with a medal.<ref name="MacLeod">{{cite web | title=1978 World Cup | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0002/print.shtml | publisher=BBC | access-date=15 May 2007 | archive-date=29 January 2006 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060129125434/http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0002/print.shtml | url-status=live }}</ref> As the squad left for the finals in Argentina, they were given an enthusiastic send-off as they were paraded around a packed [[Hampden Park]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Aitken | first=Mike | title=Ally MacLeod, a tragic hero | url=http://sport.scotsman.com/allymacleod/Ally-MacLeod-a-tragic-hero.2500029.jp | newspaper=The Scotsman | date=2 February 2004 | access-date=8 January 2008 | archive-date=9 January 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109225247/http://sport.scotsman.com/allymacleod/Ally-MacLeod-a-tragic-hero.2500029.jp | url-status=live }}</ref> Thousands more fans lined the route to [[Glasgow Prestwick International Airport|Prestwick Airport]] as the team set off for [[South America]].<ref name="MacLeod" /> Scotland lost their first game 3–1 against [[Peru national football team|Peru]] in [[Córdoba, Argentina|Córdoba]], and drew the second 1–1 against newcomers [[Iran national football team|Iran]].<ref name="MacLeod" /> The disconsolate mood of the nation was reflected by footage of MacLeod in the [[Technical area|dugout]] with his head in his hands.<ref>{{cite web | title=Ally McLeod&nbsp;– a national treasure | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/scotland/3468549.stm | first=Chick | last=Young | publisher=BBC Sport | date=7 February 2004 | access-date=15 May 2007 | archive-date=13 March 2004 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040313090901/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/3468549.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> These results meant Scotland had to defeat the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] by three clear goals to progress.<ref name="cup78" /> Despite the Dutch taking the lead, Scotland fought back to win 3–2 with a goal from [[Kenny Dalglish]] and two from [[Archie Gemmill]], the second of which is considered one of the greatest World Cup goals ever;<ref name="MacLeod" /> Gemmill beat three Dutch defenders before lifting the ball over goalkeeper [[Jan Jongbloed]] into the net.<ref name="MacLeod" /><ref name="gemmill">{{cite news | title=The lion roars&nbsp;– too late | url=http://sport.scotsman.com/tengreatfootballmatches/The-lion-roars--too.2379220.jp | newspaper=The Scotsman | date=19 November 2002 | access-date=8 January 2008 | archive-date=30 December 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230052122/http://sport.scotsman.com/tengreatfootballmatches/The-lion-roars--too.2379220.jp | url-status=live }}</ref> The victory was not sufficient to secure a place in the second round, and Scotland were eliminated on goal difference for the second successive World Cup.<ref name="cup78" />

===1980s: Jock Stein and Alex Ferguson===
[[File:Alex_Ferguson.jpg|thumb|left|180px|[[Alex Ferguson]] (pictured) briefly served as Scotland's manager after the sudden death of [[Jock Stein]] in 1985.]]
MacLeod resigned as manager shortly after the 1978 World Cup, and [[Jock Stein]], who had won nine consecutive [[list of Scottish football champions|Scottish league titles]] and the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] as manager of [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], was appointed as his successor.<ref name="managers" /> After failing to qualify for the [[UEFA Euro 1980|1980 European Championship]],<ref name="rsssf.com"/> Scotland qualified for the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]] from a tough group including [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], [[Israel national football team|Israel]] and [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]], losing just one match in the process.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scotland&nbsp;– International Matches 1981–1985 |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tabless/scot-intres1985.html |publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation |access-date=15 May 2007 |archive-date=17 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917131455/http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scot-intres1985.html |url-status=live }}</ref> They beat [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] 5–2 in their first game at the World Cup, but lost 4–1 to a [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] team containing [[Sócrates]], [[Zico (footballer)|Zico]], [[Éder Aleixo de Assis|Eder]] and [[Paulo Roberto Falcão|Falcão]].<ref name="cup82" /> Scotland were again eliminated on goal difference, after a 2–2 draw with the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]].<ref name="cup82" />

Scotland qualified for the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]], their fourth in succession, in traumatic circumstances. The squad went into their [[1985 Wales vs Scotland football match|last qualification match against Wales]] needing a point to progress to a qualifying playoff against [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]]. With only nine minutes remaining and Wales leading 1–0, Scotland were awarded a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]], which was calmly scored by [[Davie Cooper]].<ref name="stein">{{cite news | last=Brown | first=Craig | title=Stein, a national treasure | url=http://sport.scotsman.com/jockstein/Stein-a-national-treasure.2660236.jp | newspaper=The Scotsman | date=11 September 2005 | access-date=8 January 2008 | archive-date=9 January 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109231449/http://sport.scotsman.com/jockstein/Stein-a-national-treasure.2660236.jp | url-status=live }}</ref> The 1–1 draw meant that Scotland progressed, but as the players and fans celebrated, Stein suffered a heart attack and died shortly afterwards.<ref name="stein" /> His assistant [[Alex Ferguson]] took over.<ref name="managers" /> Scotland qualified by winning 2–0 against Australia in a two-leg playoff, but were eliminated from the tournament with just one point from their three matches, a goalless draw with [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] following defeats by [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]].<ref>{{cite web | title=World Cup 1986 | url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/86full.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | access-date=14 September 2008 | archive-date=1 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301052859/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/86full.html | url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 1986, [[Andy Roxburgh]] was the surprise appointment as the new manager of Scotland.<ref name = "rox">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DQ5BAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4aYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6100%2C3875913 |title=Scotland on a winner |newspaper=Evening Times |first=Chick |last=Young |date=17 July 1986 |page=20 |access-date=20 October 2012 |archive-date=12 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412221848/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DQ5BAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4aYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6100,3875913 |url-status=live }}</ref> Scotland did not succeed in qualifying for [[UEFA Euro 1988|Euro 1988]], but their 1–0 away win over [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] in the final fixture in November 1987 helped [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]] to a surprise first-place finish and qualification for the finals in [[West Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Davidson|first=Alan|title=Too late but new boys look good for future|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gNBAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kKYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6004%2C2954712|access-date=12 April 2015|newspaper=Evening Times|date=12 November 1987|page=26|archive-date=8 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308142319/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gNBAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kKYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6004%2C2954712|url-status=live}}</ref>

===1990s: Four major tournament appearances===
[[File:Scotland-holland euro 96.jpg|thumb|right|Scotland against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] at [[Villa Park]] during [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]]]]
Scotland qualified for their fifth consecutive [[1990 FIFA World Cup|World Cup in 1990]] by finishing second in their qualifying group, ahead of [[France national football team|France]].<ref>{{cite web | title=World Cup 1990 Qualifying | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/90q.html | access-date=31 August 2008 | archive-date=20 July 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220720114857/https://www.rsssf.org/tables/90q.html | url-status=live }}</ref> Scotland were drawn in a group with [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], Sweden, and Brazil, but the Scots lost 1–0 to Costa Rica.<ref name = "Italy 90">{{cite web | title=World Cup 1990 (Italy, 8 June&nbsp;– 8 July) | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/90f.html | access-date=31 August 2008 | archive-date=20 July 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220720114856/https://www.rsssf.org/tables/90f.html | url-status=live }}</ref> While they recovered to beat Sweden 2–1 in their second game, they lost to Brazil in their third match 1–0 and were again eliminated after the first round.<ref name = "Italy 90"/>

By a narrow margin, Scotland qualified for the [[UEFA European Championship]] for the first time in [[UEFA Euro 1992|1992]].<ref name="sweden">{{cite web|title=1992&nbsp;– Small but perfectly formed |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/euro/history/season=1992/intro.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070421035254/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/euro/history/season%3D1992/intro.html |archive-date=21 April 2007 |publisher=UEFA|date=5 October 2003 |access-date=15 May 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A 1–0 defeat by [[Romania national football team|Romania]] away from home left qualification dependent upon other results, but a 1–1 draw between [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] and Romania in the final group match saw Scotland squeeze through.<ref name="euro92">{{cite web | title=European Championship 1992 | url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/92e.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | access-date=15 May 2007 | archive-date=7 December 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151207181621/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/92e.html | url-status=live }}</ref> Despite playing well in matches against the Netherlands and Germany and a fine win against the [[CIS national football team|CIS]], the team was knocked out at the group stage.<ref name="euro92" /> Scotland failed to qualify for the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]]. The team finished fourth in their [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifying group]] behind [[Italy national football team|Italy]], [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] and Portugal. When it became clear that Scotland could not qualify, [[Andy Roxburgh]] resigned from his position as team manager.<ref name = "Brown highs and lows">{{cite web | title=Craig Brown's highs and lows | publisher=BBC Sport | date=7 October 2001 | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/1528293.stm | access-date=31 August 2008 | archive-date=2 December 2002 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021202193327/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/1528293.stm | url-status=live }}</ref>

New manager [[Craig Brown (footballer, born 1940)|Craig Brown]] successfully guided Scotland to the [[UEFA Euro 1996|1996 European Championship]] tournament.<ref name = "Brown highs and lows"/> The first game against the Netherlands ended 0–0, raising morale ahead of a much anticipated game against England at Wembley.<ref name = "Brown highs and lows"/> [[Gary McAllister]] missed a penalty kick, and a goal by [[Paul Gascoigne]] led to a 2–0 defeat. Scotland recovered to beat [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] 1–0 with a goal by [[Ally McCoist]]. England taking a 4–0 lead in the other match briefly put Scotland in a position to qualify, but a late goal for the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] meant that they advanced instead of Scotland on goals scored.<ref name = "Brown highs and lows"/><ref name=england96>{{cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablese/eng-intres95.html|title=England: International results 1995–1999 details|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|access-date=18 July 2010|date=14 March 2004|first=Barrie|last=Courtney|archive-date=6 December 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221206144249/https://www.rsssf.org/tablese/eng-intres95.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Brown again guided Scotland to qualification for a major tournament in 1998, and Scotland were drawn against Brazil in the opening game of the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland Open the World Cup 1998 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0042/ | publisher=BBC | access-date=16 May 2007 | archive-date=15 September 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915071230/http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0042/ | url-status=live }}</ref> [[John Collins (footballer, born 1968)|John Collins]] equalised from the penalty spot to level the score at 1–1, but a [[Tom Boyd (Scottish footballer)|Tom Boyd]] [[own goal]] led to a 2–1 defeat. Scotland drew their next game 1–1 with Norway in [[Bordeaux]],<ref name="burley" /> but the final match against [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] ended in an embarrassing 3–0 defeat.<ref name = "Brown highs and lows"/>

During the qualification for the [[UEFA Euro 2000|2000 European Championship]], Scotland faced England in a [[two-legged tie|two-legged]] playoff nicknamed the "Battle of Britain" by the media.<ref name="wembley1-0">{{cite web | title=Battle of Britain | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/special_report/1999/11/99/battle_of_britain/525203.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=17 November 1999 | access-date=11 April 2007 | archive-date=27 March 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070327234019/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1999/11/99/battle_of_britain/525203.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> Scotland won the second match 1–0 with a goal by [[Don Hutchison]], but lost the tie 2–1 on aggregate.<ref name="wembley1-0" />

===2000s: First foreign manager and 2008 near miss===
[[File:Berti Vogts cropped.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Berti Vogts]], the only foreigner to coach Scotland to date]]

Scotland failed to qualify for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]], finishing third in their qualifying group behind [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] and [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]].<ref name = "Brown highs and lows"/> This second successive failure to qualify prompted Craig Brown to resign from his position after the final qualifying match.<ref name = "Brown highs and lows"/> The [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] appointed former Germany manager [[Berti Vogts]] as Brown's successor.<ref>{{cite web | title=Vogts unveiled by Scotland | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1822296.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=15 February 2002 | access-date=12 April 2007 | archive-date=30 April 2004 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040430070645/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1822296.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> Scotland reached the qualification play-offs for [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]], where they beat the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] 1–0 at Hampden Park, but suffered a 6–0 defeat in the return leg. Poor results in friendly matches and a bad start to the 2006 World Cup qualification caused the team to drop to a record low of 77th in the [[FIFA World Rankings]].<ref name = lowrank>{{cite web | title=Scotland hit new low in rankings | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/3998817.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=10 November 2004 | access-date=12 April 2007 | archive-date=30 May 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220530134147/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/3998817.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> Vogts announced his resignation in 2004,<ref>{{cite web | title=Vogts resigns from Scotland job | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/3734094.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=1 November 2004 | access-date=12 April 2007 | archive-date=13 December 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213104913/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/3734094.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> blaming the hostile media for his departure.<ref>{{cite web | title=Berti Vogts personal statement | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/3972921.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=1 November 2004 | access-date=12 April 2007 | archive-date=9 November 2005 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051109235348/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/3972921.stm | url-status=live }}</ref>

[[Walter Smith]], a former [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] manager, was brought in to replace Vogts. Improved results meant that Scotland rose up the FIFA rankings and won the [[Kirin Cup]], a friendly competition in Japan.<ref>{{cite web | title=Japan 0–0 Scotland | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4765811.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=13 May 2006 | access-date=11 April 2007 | archive-date=22 December 2006 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061222143527/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4765811.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> Scotland failed to qualify for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], finishing third in their group behind [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and [[Norway national football team|Norway]]. Smith left the national side in January 2007 to return to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], with Scotland leading their [[2008 UEFA European Championship|Euro 2008]] qualification group.<ref>{{cite web | title=Smith appointed boss of Rangers | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/6233237.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=10 January 2007 | access-date=12 April 2007 | archive-date=23 March 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323053841/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/6233237.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> New manager [[Alex McLeish]]<ref>{{cite web | title=McLeish unveiled as Scotland boss | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/6289073.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=29 January 2007 | access-date=12 April 2007 | archive-date=31 March 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070331112445/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/6289073.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> guided Scotland to wins against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]], the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]], [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]], France and [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]], but defeats by Georgia and Italy ended their chances of qualification for Euro 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7115771.stm|title=Rise and fall of McLeish's Scotland|date=27 November 2007|access-date=2 February 2008 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> These improved results, particularly the wins against France, lifted Scotland into the top 20 of the FIFA world rankings.<ref name = "peak ranking"/>

After the narrow failure to qualify for Euro 2008, McLeish left to join [[Premier League]] club [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{cite web | title = McLeish leaves Scotland for Blues | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 27 November 2007 | url = https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7114028.stm | access-date = 27 September 2008 | archive-date = 29 November 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071129214609/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7114028.stm | url-status = live }}</ref> [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] manager [[George Burley]] was hired as the new manager, but he came in for criticism from the media after the team lost their first qualifier against [[Macedonia national football team|Macedonia]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Hunter | first = Andy | title = Fletcher backs Burley as McCulloch deepens woe | newspaper = The Guardian | date = 9 September 2008 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/sep/09/worldcup2010qualifiers.scotlandfootballteam | access-date = 27 September 2008 | location = London | archive-date = 2 May 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140502061030/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/sep/09/worldcup2010qualifiers.scotlandfootballteam | url-status = live }}</ref> After Scotland lost their fourth match 3–0 to the Netherlands,<ref>{{cite web | last = Moffat | first = Colin | title = Netherlands 3–0 Scotland | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 28 March 2009 | url = https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7963110.stm | access-date = 31 March 2009 | archive-date = 31 March 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090331111822/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7963110.stm | url-status = live }}</ref> captain [[Barry Ferguson]] and goalkeeper [[Allan McGregor]] were excluded from the starting lineup for the following match against [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] due to a "breach of discipline".<ref>{{cite web | title = Scots duo breach to be reviewed | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 1 April 2009 | url = https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7977741.stm | access-date = 2 April 2009 | archive-date = 4 April 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090404111720/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7977741.stm | url-status = live }}</ref> Despite winning 2–1 against Iceland,<ref>{{cite web |last=Moffat |first=Colin |title=Scotland 2–1 Iceland |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 April 2009 |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7971845.stm |access-date=2 April 2009 |archive-date=2 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402052107/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7971845.stm |url-status=live }}</ref> Scotland suffered a 4–0 defeat by Norway in the following qualifier, which left Scotland effectively needing to win their last two games to have a realistic chance of making the qualifying play-offs.<ref>{{cite web | last =Moffat | first =Colin | title = Scotland can bounce back&nbsp;– Burley |publisher=BBC Sport | date = 13 August 2009 | url = https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/8194452.stm | access-date = 6 September 2009 }}</ref> Scotland defeated Macedonia 2–0 in the first of those two games,<ref>{{cite web | last =Moffat | first =Colin | title = Scotland 2–0 Macedonia |publisher=BBC Sport | date = 5 September 2009 | url = https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8230555.stm | access-date = 6 September 2009 }}</ref> but were eliminated by a 1–0 loss to the Netherlands in the second game.<ref>{{cite web | last = Lindsay | first = Clive | title = Scotland 0–1 Netherlands | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 9 September 2009 | url = https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/8240464.stm | access-date = 9 September 2009 | archive-date = 2 May 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140502085010/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/8240464.stm | url-status = live }}</ref> Burley was allowed to continue in his post after a review by the SFA board,<ref>{{cite web | title = Burley remains as Scotland boss |publisher=BBC Sport| date = 15 September 2009 | url = https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/8256276.stm | access-date = 16 September 2009 }}</ref> but a subsequent 3–0 friendly defeat by Wales led to his dismissal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8361602.stm |title=Burley sacked as Scotland manager |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=16 November 2009 |date=16 November 2009 |archive-date=9 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109035147/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/8361602.stm |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2010s: Failures to qualify===
[[File:Strachan Gordon.jpg|thumb|right|[[Gordon Strachan]] was appointed Scotland manager in January 2013.]]
The SFA appointed [[Craig Levein]] as head coach of the national team in December 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/8424274.stm |title=Levein appointed Scotland manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 December 2009 |access-date=16 October 2010 |archive-date=5 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210505115405/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/8424274.stm |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying]], Scotland were grouped with [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]], [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]], the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] and world champions [[Spain men's national football team|Spain]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/scotland/8970226.stm |title=Scotland 2–1 Liechtenstein |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 September 2010 |access-date=7 September 2010 |last=Lindsay |first=Clive |archive-date=29 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029071723/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/scotland/8970226.stm |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name = "three wins"/> They took just four points from the first four games, leaving the team needing three wins from their remaining four games to have a realistic chance of progression.<ref name = "three wins">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/more-scottish-football/miller-insists-three-wins-will-seal-play-off-place-1.1061204 |title=Miller insists three wins will seal play-off place |newspaper=The Herald |date=13 October 2010 |access-date=13 October 2010 |last=Macpherson |first=Graeme |archive-date=16 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101016164913/http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/more-scottish-football/miller-insists-three-wins-will-seal-play-off-place-1.1061204 |url-status=dead }}</ref> They only managed two wins and a draw and were eliminated after a 3–1 defeat by Spain in their last match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/15232020|first=Annie|last=McGuire |title=Spain 3–1 Scotland |publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 October 2011 |access-date=11 October 2011}}</ref> Levein left his position as head coach following a poor start to [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification]], having taken just two points from four games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20205303 |title=Craig Levein exits as Scotland coach following talks |first=Chris |last=McLaughlin |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 November 2012 |access-date=5 November 2012 |archive-date=6 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106000007/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20205303 |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[Gordon Strachan]] was appointed Scotland manager in January 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21023913 |title=Gordon Strachan confirmed as Scotland coach |first=Chris |last=McLaughlin |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 January 2013 |access-date=15 January 2013 |archive-date=15 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115092053/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21023913 |url-status=live }}</ref> but defeats in his first two competitive matches meant that Scotland were the first UEFA team to be eliminated from the 2014 World Cup qualification.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/international/219124-scotland-officially-first-uefa-nation-eliminated-from-world-cup-qualifying/ |title=Scotland officially first UEFA nation eliminated from World Cup qualifying |first=Grant |last=Russell |publisher=STV Sport |date=26 March 2013 |access-date=26 March 2013 |archive-date=2 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130402043201/http://sport.stv.tv/football/international/219124-scotland-officially-first-uefa-nation-eliminated-from-world-cup-qualifying/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> Scotland finished their qualification section by winning three of their last four matches, including two victories against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22787925 |title=Croatia 0–1 Scotland |publisher=BBC Sport |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont |date=7 June 2013 |access-date=8 June 2013 |archive-date=13 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613020116/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22787925 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24439813 |title=Scotland 2–0 Croatia |publisher=BBC Sport |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont |date=15 October 2013 |access-date=14 July 2014 |archive-date=18 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518152350/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24439813 |url-status=live }}</ref> 

[[UEFA Euro 2016]] expanded from 16 teams to 24.<ref name = "bumpy">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34532300 |title=A bumpy ride: Gordon Strachan and Scotland |first=Andy |last=Burke |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 October 2015 |access-date=16 October 2015 |archive-date=17 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017045235/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34532300 |url-status=live }}</ref> After losing their first qualifier in [[Germany national football team|Germany]], Scotland recorded home wins against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]], the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and [[Gibraltar national football team|Gibraltar]].<ref name = "bumpy"/> [[Steven Fletcher (footballer)|Steven Fletcher]] scored the first [[hat-trick]] for Scotland since 1969 in the game with Gibraltar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32006329 |title=Scotland 6–1 Gibraltar |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 March 2015 |access-date=17 November 2019 |archive-date=23 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023192656/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32006329 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later in the group, Scotland produced an "insipid" performance as they lost 1–0 in Georgia.<ref name = "bumpy"/> A home defeat by Germany and a late equalising goal by [[Poland national football team|Poland]] eliminated Scotland from contention.<ref name = "bumpy"/> After a win against Gibraltar in the last qualifier, Strachan agreed a new contract with the SFA.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34540057 |title=Gordon Strachan: Scotland boss signs new two-year contract |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 October 2015 |access-date=16 October 2015 |archive-date=15 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015211420/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34540057 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualification]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], Scotland were drawn in the same group as England, facing their rivals in a competitive fixture for the first time since 1999.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|title=England to play World Cup qualifier against Scotland on a Friday night|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jul/26/england-scotland-world-cup-2018-qualifier-friday-night|access-date=20 October 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|agency=Press Association|date=26 July 2015|archive-date=12 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012202452/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jul/26/england-scotland-world-cup-2018-qualifier-friday-night|url-status=live}}</ref> On 11 November 2016, England beat Scotland 3–0 at Wembley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37868651|title=World Cup Qualifying – European – Group F|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=11 November 2016|access-date=29 November 2016|archive-date=17 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817145932/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37868651|url-status=live}}</ref> The return match saw [[Leigh Griffiths]] score two late free-kicks to give Scotland a 2–1 lead, but [[Harry Kane]] scored in added time to force a 2–2 draw.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40141512 |title=Scotland 2–2 England |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=10 June 2017 |access-date=14 June 2017 |archive-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024193030/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40141512 |url-status=live }}</ref> A draw in [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]] in the final game of the group ended Scottish hopes of a play-off position, and Strachan subsequently left his position by mutual consent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scotland: Gordon Strachan leaves his position as national manager|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41598733|access-date=12 October 2017|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=12 October 2017|archive-date=12 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012134207/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41598733|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2018, Alex McLeish was appointed manager for the second time.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murray|first1=Ewan|title=Alex McLeish says it was his 'destiny' to return as Scotland manager|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/feb/16/football-scotland-manager-alex-mcleish|access-date=17 March 2018|newspaper=The Guardian|date=16 February 2018|archive-date=16 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316134821/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/feb/16/football-scotland-manager-alex-mcleish|url-status=live}}</ref> The team won their group in the [[2018–19 UEFA Nations League]], but McLeish left in April 2019 after a poor start to [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]], including a 3–0 loss to 117th-ranked [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Scotland: Alex McLeish exits after poor start to Euro 2020 qualifying |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47767790 |access-date=18 April 2019 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=18 April 2019 |archive-date=18 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418111623/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47767790 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2020s: Steve Clarke and three tournament qualifications ===
[[File:First Minister meets with Scottish National Football Team - 55168603663.jpg|thumb|right|Scotland squad meet with [[First Minister of Scotland|First Minister]] [[John Swinney]] ahead of the [[2026 World Cup]]]] 
[[Steve Clarke]] was appointed Scotland manager in May 2019.<ref name = clarkeappt>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48303984 |title=Steve Clarke is named new Scotland manager |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=20 May 2019 |access-date=20 May 2019 |archive-date=20 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520141503/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48303984 |url-status=live }}</ref> The team failed to qualify automatically for [[UEFA Euro 2020]], but consecutive victories in [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootouts]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying play-offs|playoffs]] against [[Israel national football team|Israel]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51955716 |title=Scotland 0–0 Israel |first=Scott |last=Mullen |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=8 October 2020 |access-date=9 October 2020 |archive-date=9 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201009014013/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51955716 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] put Scotland into their first major tournament since 1998.<ref name = 2020qual>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54819938 |title=Scotland win shootout to end 23-year wait for a major tournament |last=Watt |first=Martin |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=12 November 2020 |access-date=12 November 2020 |archive-date=18 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210318190409/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54819938 |url-status=live }}</ref> Defeats by the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] and [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], either side of a goalless draw with [[England national football team|England]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/jun/18/england-scotland-euro-2020-match-report |title=England frustrated by steely Scotland in Euro 2020 stalemate at Wembley |first=David |last=Hytner |newspaper=The Guardian |date=18 June 2021 |access-date=27 August 2021 |archive-date=30 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220530134149/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/jun/18/england-scotland-euro-2020-match-report |url-status=live }}</ref> meant that Scotland finished bottom of [[UEFA Euro 2020 Group D|Group D]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198439 |title=Croatia 3–1 Scotland |first=Scott |last=Mullen |website=BBC Sport |date=22 June 2021 |access-date=23 June 2021 |archive-date=22 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210622233227/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198439 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Six consecutive wins later that year meant that Scotland finished second in [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group F|Group F]] of [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]].<ref name = 2022playoffs/> This progressed the team into the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA second round|play-offs]], where they were paired with [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] in a semi-final at Hampden; Scotland lost 3–1.<ref name = 2022playoffs>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59425818 |title=Scotland to face Ukraine in World Cup play-off semi-finals |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 November 2021 |accessdate=27 November 2021 |archive-date=27 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127062125/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59425818 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that year, Scotland won their [[2022&ndash;23 UEFA Nations League B|Nations League]] group and promotion to League A.<ref name = krakow/>

The Scots began their [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] campaign with five wins out of five, including a 2–0 victory over Spain at Hampden.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Banks |first=Ben |date=9 September 2023 |title=World media reacts to 'flawless' Scotland romp in Cyprus |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/world-media-reacts-flawless-scotland-30899674 |access-date=14 September 2023 |website=Daily Record |archive-date=10 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230910154836/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/world-media-reacts-flawless-scotland-30899674 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite losing their sixth match, the return game against Spain, they qualified for [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]] with two matches to spare after [[Norway national football team|Norway]] lost 1–0 to Spain. This meant they qualified through a qualifying group to reach a major tournament for the first time since 1998.<ref name = 2024qual>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67092471 |title=Scotland qualify for Euro 2024 finals in Germany as Spain beat Norway |website=BBC Sport |date=15 October 2023 |access-date=16 October 2023 |archive-date=15 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231015234947/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67092471 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Robson |first=James |date=15 October 2023 |title=Gavi goal against Norway sees Spain and Scotland qualify for European Championship |url=https://apnews.com/article/euro-2024-qualifiers-spain-scotland-croatia-f0a67848ef9980ef0bd21809732e26e5 |access-date=19 December 2023 |website=AP News |archive-date=19 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231219163926/https://apnews.com/article/euro-2024-qualifiers-spain-scotland-croatia-f0a67848ef9980ef0bd21809732e26e5 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Scotland reporter notebook: How Steve Clarke's side avoided stress to qualify for Euro 2024 |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12017/12985281/scotland-reporter-notebook-how-steve-clarkes-side-avoided-stress-to-qualify-for-euro-2024 |access-date=19 December 2023 |website=Sky Sports |archive-date=19 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231219163926/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12017/12985281/scotland-reporter-notebook-how-steve-clarkes-side-avoided-stress-to-qualify-for-euro-2024 |url-status=live }}</ref> Scotland was drawn to face [[Germany national football team|Germany]], [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] in [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]]. They were thrashed 5–1 by the Germans in the opening match,<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 June 2024 |title=Scotland fans left stranded as Euro 2024 party derailed by German trains |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/life_style/24384616.scotland-fans-face-euro-2024-train-nightmare-day-one/ |access-date=14 June 2024 |website=The Herald}}</ref> drew 1–1 with the Swiss and lost 1–0 to Hungary to once again finish bottom of the group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/scotland-euro-2024-hungary-steve-clarke-b2567638.html|title=The brutal truth behind Scotland's Euro 2024 heartbreak &#124; The Independent|website=[[Independent.co.uk]] |date=24 June 2024 }}</ref> It was estimated that around 200,000 Scotland fans travelled to Euro 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 June 2024 |title=Scotland fans endure humbling Euro opener against Germany |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/cjmm49vempdo |access-date=19 June 2024 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

In their [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2026 World Cup qualification]] group Scotland drew with Denmark away, beat Belarus twice and Greece at home while losing away. On 18 November 2025, they beat [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] 4&ndash;2 at home in the last match of the section to qualify for their ninth World Cup finals, and their first since 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/ce8glxdnx9wt#Report |title=Scotland vs Denmark LIVE: UEFA World Cup Qualifiers - watch, listen, team news, updates, report, reaction, stats & head-to-head |website=BBC Sport |date=18 November 2025 |accessdate=18 November 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cew4v8vgkyyo|title='Scotland cash in almost 30 years of glorious failure as dreams come true'|date=19 November 2025|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 November 2025}}</ref>

==Stadium==
{{Main|Scotland national football team home stadium}}
[[File:Hampden Park, Glasgow.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Hampden Park]] in Glasgow, the home stadium of the Scotland national football team]]
[[Hampden Park]] in Glasgow is the traditional home of the Scotland team and is described by the SFA as the National Stadium.<ref>{{cite web | title=Hampden Park | url=http://guide.visitscotland.com/vs/guide/5,en,SCH1/objectId,SPF47918Svs,curr,GBP,season,at1,selectedEntry,home/home.html | publisher=Scottish Tourist Board | access-date=15 September 2008 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007152159/http://guide.visitscotland.com/vs/guide/5,en,SCH1/objectId,SPF47918Svs,curr,GBP,season,at1,selectedEntry,home/home.html | archive-date=7 October 2008}}</ref> The present stadium is one of three stadiums to have used the name. Stadiums named Hampden Park have hosted international matches since 1878. The present site was opened in 1903 and became the primary home ground of the Scotland team from 1906. The attendance record of 149,415 was set by the Scotland v England match in 1937.<ref name="hampden">{{cite web | title=Hampden Park | url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/uefacup/finals/newsid=511874.html | publisher=UEFA | date=14 March 2007 | access-date=16 May 2007 | archive-date=23 May 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523025816/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/uefacup/finals/newsid=511874.html | url-status=dead }}</ref> Safety regulations reduced the capacity to 81,000 by 1977 and the stadium was completely redeveloped during the 1990s, giving the present capacity of 52,000. Hampden is rated as a category four (elite) stadium within the [[UEFA stadium categories]], having previously held the five-star status under the old rating system.<ref>{{cite web | title=Hampden | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/image_gallery.cfm?page=3089 | website=scottishfa.co.uk | publisher=Scottish Football Association | access-date=17 February 2013 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005170524/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/image_gallery.cfm?page=3089 | archive-date=5 October 2012}}</ref>

Some [[exhibition game|friendly match]]es are played at smaller venues. [[Pittodrie Stadium]] in [[Aberdeen]] and [[Easter Road Stadium|Easter Road]] in [[Edinburgh]] were both used as venues during 2017. Other stadiums were also used while Hampden was being redeveloped during the 1990s. [[Celtic Park]], [[Ibrox Stadium]], Pittodrie Stadium and [[Rugby Park]] all hosted matches during the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]] qualifying campaign,<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland&nbsp;– International Matches 1996–2001 | url=https://www.rsssf.org/tabless/scot-intres2001.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | access-date=15 September 2008 | archive-date=4 February 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230204052407/https://rsssf.org/tabless/scot-intres2001.html | url-status=live }}</ref> while [[Tynecastle Stadium]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland National Team Match Details | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=57886 | publisher=Scottish Football Association | access-date=16 May 2007 | archive-date=30 September 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181646/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=57886 | url-status=live }}</ref> Pittodrie,<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland National Team Match Details | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=57887 | publisher=Scottish Football Association | access-date=16 May 2007 | archive-date=12 December 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212024837/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=57887 | url-status=live }}</ref> Celtic Park and Ibrox Stadium were used for [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]] qualifying matches. Since the last redevelopment to Hampden was completed in 1999, Scotland have played most of their competitive matches there. The most recent exception to this rule was in 2014, when Hampden was temporarily converted into an athletics stadium for the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30044407 |title=Scotland: Gordon Strachan hails Celtic Park atmosphere |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=13 November 2014 |access-date=14 October 2015 |archive-date=19 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019152355/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30044407 |url-status=live }}</ref> The SFA purchased Hampden from [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53648727 |title=Scottish FA takes ownership of Hampden Park |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 August 2020 |access-date=4 August 2020 |archive-date=19 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201019115404/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53648727 |url-status=live }}</ref> and all of Scotland's home games have been played there since then.

==Media coverage==
Matches played by Scotland are presently broadcast by [[BBC Scotland]], under an arrangement reached with UEFA in March 2025.<ref name = bbc2026>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c14jg406vj8o  |title=Scotland men's internationals to be shown live on BBC |website=BBC Sport |date=7 March 2025 |accessdate=11 March 2025}}</ref> [[Sky Sports]],<ref name = "Salmond hits out">{{cite news  | title=Salmond hits out over TV football  | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/7267706.stm  | work=BBC News  | date=27 February 2008  | access-date=4 October 2008  | archive-date=29 January 2009  | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090129135347/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7267706.stm  | url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12011/8712153/UEFA-Euro-2016-and-FIFA-2018-World-Cup-qualifiers-live-on-Sky-Sports |title=UEFA Euro 2016 and FIFA 2018 World Cup qualifiers live on Sky Sports |publisher=Sky Sports |date=14 May 2013 |access-date=14 May 2013 |archive-date=8 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108193940/http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12011/8712153/UEFA-Euro-2016-and-FIFA-2018-World-Cup-qualifiers-live-on-Sky-Sports |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name = serbia>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54852816 |title=Scotland & Northern Ireland Euro 2020 play-off finals free-to-air |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=7 November 2020 |access-date=7 November 2020 |archive-date=7 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201107114004/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54852816 |url-status=live }}</ref>  [[STV (TV channel)|STV]], [[Setanta Sports]],<ref name = "Salmond hits out"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/8115360.stm |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |access-date=16 August 2010 |date=23 June 2009 |title=Setanta goes into administration |archive-date=25 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625144745/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8115360.stm |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]],<ref>{{cite news | title=Channel 5 Ad Campaign Promoting Scotland v Croatia Coverage | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2000/oct/10/channelfive.broadcasting | newspaper=The Guardian | date=10 October 2000 | access-date=9 October 2008 | location=London | first=Jason | last=Deans | archive-date=2 May 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502061635/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2000/oct/10/channelfive.broadcasting | url-status=live }}</ref> [[BT Sport]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/world-cup-qualifier-macedonia-v-scotland-match-preview-8806857.html |title=World Cup qualifier: Macedonia v Scotland match preview |newspaper=The Independent |first=Tom |last=Roddy |date=10 September 2013 |access-date=12 September 2013 |location=London |archive-date=13 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913131750/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/world-cup-qualifier-macedonia-v-scotland-match-preview-8806857.html |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Pick (TV channel)|Pick]],<ref name = serbia/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/sport/football/2020-11-12/serbia-scotland-watch-live-kick-off-time-tv-channel-2020-21/ |title=What channel is Serbia v Scotland on? Kick off time, live stream and latest team news |first=Joe |last=Short |newspaper=Radio Times |date=12 November 2020 |access-date=13 November 2020 |archive-date=12 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201112200955/https://www.radiotimes.com/news/sport/football/2020-11-12/serbia-scotland-watch-live-kick-off-time-tv-channel-2020-21/ |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Premier Sports]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/premier-sports-win-scotland-broadcast-27018250 |title=Premier Sports win Scotland broadcast rights for Nations League and Euro 2024 qualifiers in major new TV deal |first=Gavin |last=Berry |newspaper=Daily Record |date=20 May 2022 |accessdate=20 May 2022 |archive-date=20 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220520103527/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/premier-sports-win-scotland-broadcast-27018250 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Viaplay]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61241263 |title=Scotland: Nordic streaming service Viaplay buys rights to men's matches from 2024 |website=BBC Sport |date=27 April 2022 |accessdate=27 April 2022 |archive-date=27 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220427100519/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61241263 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/66256891 |title=Viaplay: Broadcaster of Scotland games and Scottish League Cup to pull out of UK |website=BBC Sport |date=20 July 2023 |accessdate=22 November 2024}}</ref> [[ITV4]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/football/articles/itv-secure-deal-to-air-scotland-and-northern-ireland-national-teams-nations |title=ITV Secure Deal To Air Scotland And Northern Ireland National Teams Nations League Fixtures |website=ITV |date=4 September 2024 |accessdate=22 November 2024}}</ref> and [[YouTube]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/c0m0jjw997vo |title=Scotland Nations League matches only available on YouTube |website=BBC News |date=10 October 2024 |accessdate=22 November 2024 |first=Chris |last=McLaughlin}}</ref> have previously shown Scotland fixtures. Matches are also broadcast with full commentary on [[BBC Radio Scotland]] and, when schedules allow, [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] also.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/scotland/8918078.stm |title=BBC to screen Scotland away ties on road to Euro 2012 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=16 August 2010 |access-date=16 August 2010 |archive-date=23 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240323175718/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/scotland/8918078.stm |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=BBC Radio 5 Live Coverage | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0070hx6 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080718003547/http://www.bbc.co.uk/fivelive/sport/commentaries.shtml | archive-date= 18 July 2008 |publisher=BBC | date=9 October 2008 | url-status=live | access-date=9 October 2008}}</ref>

Until the BBC acquired the rights in 2025, Scotland matches were regularly broadcast on [[Pay television|subscription services]]. These arrangements were criticised in 2008 by the [[Scottish Government]], who argued that all competitive internationals should be a [[Ofcom Code on Sports and Other Listed and Designated Events|Listed Event]] that can only be broadcast on [[free-to-air]] television.<ref name = "Salmond hits out"/><ref>{{cite news | title=Scotland games 'should be free' | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7639315.stm | work=BBC News | date=27 September 2008 | access-date=4 October 2008 | archive-date=1 October 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081001195007/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7639315.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> Live coverage is only restricted during major tournament finals, which are normally shown on BBC Scotland or STV.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/scotland-vs-czech-republic-tv-24309802 |title=BBC pundits for Scotland's clash with Czech Republic revealed |newspaper=Daily Record |first=Liam |last=Bryce |date=13 June 2021 |accessdate=27 May 2022 |archive-date=27 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220527204830/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/scotland-vs-czech-republic-tv-24309802 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-10715529 |title=Scotland games to stay on pay TV |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=21 July 2010 |access-date=24 July 2010 |archive-date=23 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723174354/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-10715529 |url-status=live }}</ref> The SFA argued that limiting the rights for other games, such as qualifying matches, would reduce the revenue from that source.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://sport.scotsman.com/scotlandsfootballteam/Smith-fires-a-warning-shot.5494310.jp | title = Smith fires a warning shot to Westminster over Scotland TV rights | newspaper = The Scotsman | publisher = Johnston Publishing | date = 26 July 2009 | access-date = 13 August 2009 | archive-date = 27 April 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110427032821/http://sport.scotsman.com/scotlandsfootballteam/Smith-fires-a-warning-shot.5494310.jp | url-status = live }}</ref> 

The [[Scottish Affairs Select Committee|Scottish Affairs Committee]] of MPs in the [[House of Commons (United Kingdom)|British House of Commons]] published a report in 2023 calling for more co-operation between rights holders.<ref name = sac>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-64824142 |title=Fans 'should be able to watch Scotland men's matches for free' - MPs report |website=BBC News |date=2 March 2023 |accessdate=2 March 2023 |archive-date=2 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230302155250/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-64824142 |url-status=live }}</ref> They also pointed to the greater coverage given on free-to-air television for qualifying matches involving [[England national football team|England]] and [[Wales national football team|Wales]].<ref name = sac/> Two friendly matches in 2024 were shown on the BBC, following an agreement with Viaplay,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68554565 |title=BBC to show Scotland games against Northern Ireland & Finland |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2024 |accessdate=13 March 2024 |archive-date=13 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313125605/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68554565 |url-status=live }}</ref> and in March 2025 the BBC secured rights for all Scotland matches between then and the 2026 World Cup.<ref name = bbc2026/>

==Colours==
{{Commons|Scotland national football team kits}} 
{{Football kit box
|align= right
|pattern_la = _sco96h
