Scotland traditionally wears dark blue shirts with white shorts and dark blue socks, the colours of the [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] team who represented Scotland in the first international.<ref name="oldest" /> The blue Scotland shirt was earlier used in a February 1872 [[rugby union|rugby]] international, with reports stating that "the scotch were easily distinguishable by their uniform of blue jerseys.... the jerseys having the [[thistle]] embroidered".<ref>Daily News (London, England), Tuesday, 6 February 1872; Issue 8042.</ref> The thistle had previously been worn to represent Scotland in the 1871 rugby international, but on ''brown'' shirts.<ref>''[[The Herald (Scotland)|Glasgow Herald]]'', 28 March 1871; Issue 9746.</ref> The shirt is embroidered with a crest based upon the lion rampant of the [[Royal Standard of Scotland]].

Another style often used by Scotland comprises blue shirts, white shorts and red socks, whilst several kits have used navy shorts and socks.<ref name="HFK 2000-10">{{cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/international/scotland/scotland-2000-2010.html|title=Scotland 2000–2010|publisher=Historical Football Kits|access-date=4 October 2020|archive-date=16 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210116232633/http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/international/scotland/scotland-2000-2010.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/international/scotland/scotland-2020-2029.html|title=Scotland 2020–2029|publisher=Historical Football Kits|access-date=4 October 2020|archive-date=29 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200729215103/http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/international/scotland/scotland-2020-2029.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Navy is routinely used as alternative colours for the shorts and socks when Scotland faces a team who share the same colours for these items, but when the home shirt is still appropriate.<ref name="HFK 2010-19">{{cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/international/scotland/scotland-2010-2019.html|title=Scotland 2010–2019|publisher=Historical Football Kits|access-date=4 October 2020|archive-date=9 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201009015522/http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/international/scotland/scotland-2010-2019.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

From 1994 to 1996, a [[tartan]] kit was used; this kit was worn in all three of Scotland's matches at [[UEFA Euro 1996]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland | url=http://www.kitclassics.co.uk/Internl.htm | publisher=Kit Classics | access-date=5 September 2007 | archive-date=12 September 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070912120900/http://www.kitclassics.co.uk/Internl.htm | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/international/scotland/scotland-1980-2000.html|title=Scotland 1980–2000|publisher=Historical Football Kits|access-date=4 October 2020|archive-date=30 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200630115948/http://historicalkits.co.uk/international/scotland/scotland-1980-2000.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Andrew Watson Footballer.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Scotland players, including [[Andrew Watson (footballer, born 1856)|Andrew Watson]] (top centre), wearing an atypical light blue-and-white hooped jersey in 1882]]

Scotland have not always played in dark blue; on a number of occasions between 1881 and 1951 they played in the primrose and pink racing colours of [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery]].<ref>[https://www.andrewwatsoncorinthian.co.uk/Rosebery-colours Lord Rosebery's Colours] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211028172717/https://www.andrewwatsoncorinthian.co.uk/rosebery-colours |date=28 October 2021 }}, Alistair Firth, Andrew Watson: Corinthian, August 2020</ref> A former [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], Lord Rosebery was an influential figure in Scottish football, serving as honorary President of the SFA and [[Edinburgh]] team [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]. His colours were used most frequently in the first decade of the 20th century. When Scotland defeated England 4–1 in [[1899&ndash;1900 British Home Championship|1900]], Lord Rosebery remarked, "I have never seen my colours so well sported since [[Ladas (horse)|Ladas]] won the [[Epsom Derby|Derby]]".<ref name="Rosebery">{{cite web | title=1900 Rosebery Shirt | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=236 | publisher=Scottish Football Association | access-date=31 May 2007 | archive-date=5 November 2005 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051105061120/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=236 | url-status=live }}</ref> Rosebery colours were revived as a [[away colours|change kit]] for the [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-magazine-monitor-26371625 |title=The beauty/horror of the garish new Scotland away strip |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=27 February 2014 |access-date=27 February 2014 |first=Steven |last=Brocklehurst |archive-date=2 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230502162859/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-magazine-monitor-26371625 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/26/scotlands-new-away-kit-beckham-glory-days |title=Scotland's away kit: 'A rare occasion, unknown since Beckham's glory days' |first1=John |last1=Ashdown |first2=Hadley |last2=Freeman |newspaper=The Guardian |date=26 February 2014 |access-date=27 February 2014 |archive-date=10 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230410133032/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/26/scotlands-new-away-kit-beckham-glory-days |url-status=live }}</ref>

Change colours vary, but are most commonly white or yellow shirts with blue shorts.<ref>{{cite book |last=Devlin |first=John |title=True Colours 2 |publisher=A & C Black |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-7136-7928-1}}</ref> In 2016–17, Scotland wore pink shirts with black shorts and socks as the away kit; the kit was additionally used in a single home match against [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]] due to both Slovakia kits clashing with the Scotland home kit, which featured white sleeves.<ref name="HFK 2010-19"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotlandfootballstats.co.uk/strips/away-2015|title=Away (2015–2017)|publisher=ScotlandFootballStats|access-date=4 October 2020|archive-date=29 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200929161538/http://scotlandfootballstats.co.uk/strips/away-2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/1399288-scotland-to-play-in-pink-kit-against-slovakia-at-hampden?top|title=Scotland to play in pink kit against Slovakia at Hampden|website=STV News|publisher=STV|date=5 October 2017|access-date=4 October 2020|archive-date=23 March 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240323175932/https://archive.news.stv.tv/sport/1399288-scotland-to-play-in-pink-kit-against-slovakia-at-hampden.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Third kits have been produced on two occasions. Amber shirts, navy shorts and navy socks were used in 2005–06, as the alternative sky blue shirts were unsuitable when Scotland travelled to teams wearing any shade of blue shirt, while an all 'cherry red' kit was used a single time against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualification|Euro 2008 qualifiers]] in 2007.<ref name="HFK 2000-10"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotlandfootballstats.co.uk/strips/third-2004|title=Third (2004–2006)|publisher=ScotlandFootballStats|access-date=4 October 2020|archive-date=10 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201010082641/http://www.scotlandfootballstats.co.uk/strips/third-2004|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotlandfootballstats.co.uk/strips/third-2007|title=Third (2007)|publisher=ScotlandFootballStats|access-date=4 October 2020|archive-date=7 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201007165416/http://www.scotlandfootballstats.co.uk/strips/third-2007|url-status=live}}</ref> Salmon pink was again adopted as a change colour ahead of the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026 World Cup]], although the SFA described it as "scarlet red".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/c1d9pnl9lv1o |first=Claire |last=Thomson |title=Scotland set to look pretty in pink at the World Cup |website=BBC News |date=23 March 2026 |accessdate=24 March 2026}}</ref>

===Crest===
The current version of the crest is a roundel similar to the crest used from 1961 to 1988 enclosing a shield, with "Scotland" written on the top and "Est<!--established--> 1873" on the bottom. In the shield background there are 11 thistles, representing the national flower of Scotland, in addition to the lion rampant. Since 2005, the SFA have supported the use of [[Scottish Gaelic]] on the national team's strip in recognition of the language's status in Scotland.<ref>{{cite web | title=Gaelic added to Scotland strips | website=BBC News | publisher=BBC | date=24 August 2006 | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/highlands_and_islands/5282936.stm | access-date=31 August 2008 | archive-date=16 September 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916002457/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/highlands_and_islands/5282936.stm | url-status=live }}</ref>

