==Supporters==
{{Main|Tartan Army}}

Scotland fans are collectively known as the [[Tartan Army]]. During the 1970s, Scotland fans were known for their [[football hooligan|hooliganism]] in England, particularly after they [[pitch invasion|invaded]] the [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] pitch and destroyed the goalposts after the England v Scotland match in 1977.<ref name="tartan2">{{cite book |editor-last=Smith |editor-first=Adrian |editor2=Porter, Dilwyn |title=Sport and National Identity in the Post-War World |publisher=Routledge |year=2004 |isbn=0-415-28300-0}} p77</ref> Since then, the Tartan Army have won awards from [[UEFA]] for their combination of vocal support, friendly nature and charity work.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Tartan Army | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=1205 | publisher=Scottish Football Association | access-date=11 April 2007 | archive-date=30 December 2006 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230205916/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=1205 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Tartan Army Sunshine Appeal | url=http://www.tasunshineappeal.co.uk/ | publisher=Tartan Army Sunshine Appeal | access-date=16 May 2007 | archive-date=23 April 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070423185032/http://www.tasunshineappeal.co.uk/ | url-status=live }}</ref> The Tartan Army have been awarded a [[Sportsmanship|Fair Play]] prize by the [[Belgium at the Olympics|Belgian Olympic Committee]]<ref name="t-army">{{cite web | title=Tartan Army wins fair play award | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/1682841.stm | website=BBC Sport | publisher=BBC | date=29 November 2001 | access-date=16 May 2007 | archive-date=16 November 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201116080121/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/scotland/1682841.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> and were named as the best supporters during the [[1992 UEFA European Championship|1992 European Championship]].<ref name="t-army" /> The fans were also presented with a trophy for non-violence in sport and were voted by journalists to be the best supporters for their sense of fair play and sporting spirit at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]] in France.<ref>{{cite web | title=World Cup&nbsp;– France 1998 | url= http://www.t-army.com/tar_hool.html | publisher= t-army.com | access-date=12 June 2007|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070818131232/http://www.t-army.com/tar_hool.html |archive-date = 18 August 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>

