===Honoured players===
The [[Scottish Football Association]] operates a [[Scotland Men's International Roll of Honour|roll of honour]] for every player who has made more than 50 appearances for Scotland.<ref name="roll of honour">{{cite web |title=International Roll of Honour |publisher=[[Scottish Football Association]] |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scotland/roll-of-honour/mens-roll-of-honour/ |access-date=10 November 2020 |archive-date=9 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109195640/https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scotland/roll-of-honour/mens-roll-of-honour/ |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2026|May}} there are 43 members of this roll,<ref name = "roll of honour"/> with [[Kieran Tierney]] the most recent addition to the list. The qualifying mark of 50 appearances means that many notable Scotland players including [[Jim Baxter]], [[Davie Cooper]], [[Hughie Gallacher]] (and every other pre-Second World War player), [[Archie Gemmill]], [[John Greig]], [[Jimmy Johnstone]], [[Billy McNeill]], [[Bobby Murdoch]] and [[Lawrie Reilly]] are not on the roll of honour.

The [[Scottish Football Museum]] operates a [[Scottish Football Hall of Fame|hall of fame]] which is open to players and managers involved in [[football in Scotland|Scottish football]]. This means that membership is not restricted to people who have played for Scotland; inductees include [[Brian Laudrup]] and [[Henrik Larsson]], as well as [[John McGovern (footballer, born 1949)|John McGovern]] who never played in Scotland or gained an international cap.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scottish Football Hall of Fame Dinner 2013, Celebrating 10 years of the Scottish Football Hall of Fame|url=http://www.scottishfootballmuseum.org.uk/hall-of-fame/2013.html|publisher=Scottish Football Museum|access-date=15 November 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110230226/http://www.scottishfootballmuseum.org.uk/hall-of-fame/2013.html|archive-date=10 November 2013}}</ref> [[Sportscotland]] operates the [[Scottish Sports Hall of Fame]], which has [[Scottish Sports Hall of Fame#Football|inducted some footballers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sporting legends honoured in Scottish Sports Hall of Fame|url=http://www.sportscotland.org.uk/news/sportscotland/newsarchive/2012/sporting_legends_honoured_in_scottish_sports_hall_of_fame/|access-date=14 October 2015|publisher=Sportscotland|date=13 October 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304042828/http://www.sportscotland.org.uk/news/sportscotland/newsarchive/2012/sporting_legends_honoured_in_scottish_sports_hall_of_fame/|archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>

==Records==
{{Main|Scotland national football team records and statistics}}
===Team records===
The largest margin of victory achieved by a Scotland side is 11–0 against [[Ireland national football team (IFA)|Ireland]] in the [[1901 British Home Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland&nbsp;– International Matches 1901–1910 | url=https://www.rsssf.org/tabless/scot-intres1910.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | date=6 June 2008 | access-date=1 September 2007 | archive-date=22 March 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230322071544/https://www.rsssf.org/tabless/scot-intres1910.html | url-status=live }}</ref> The record defeat occurred during the [[1954 FIFA World Cup]], a 7–0 deficit against reigning world champions [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]].<ref>{{cite web | title=World Cup | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/image_gallery.cfm?page=3123 | website=scottishfa.co.uk | publisher=Scottish Football Association | access-date=17 February 2013 | archive-date=26 October 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026211713/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/image_gallery.cfm?page=3123 | url-status=live }}</ref>

Scotland's [[1937 British Home Championship]] match against England set a new world record for a football attendance. The Hampden Park crowd was officially recorded as 149,415, though the true figure is unknown as a large number of additional fans gained unauthorised entry. This attendance was surpassed 13 years later by the [[Uruguay v Brazil (1950 FIFA World Cup)|decisive match]] of the [[1950 FIFA World Cup]], but remains a European record.<ref>{{cite news | last=Coates | first=Jonathan | title=The day Hampden Park sat on top of the world | url=http://heritage.scotsman.com/top-stories/The-day-Hampden-Park-sat.3276773.jp?CommentPage=1&CommentPageLength=1000 | newspaper=The Scotsman | date=14 April 2007 | access-date=17 September 2008 | archive-date=9 January 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109082019/http://heritage.scotsman.com/top-stories/The-day-Hampden-Park-sat.3276773.jp?CommentPage=1&CommentPageLength=1000 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=McLeish: We can be heroes | url= https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/news/newsid=638588.html | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071117070930/http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/news/newsid=638588.html | url-status= dead | archive-date= 17 November 2007 | publisher=FIFA| date=16 November 2007 | access-date=17 September 2008}}</ref>

===Player records===
====Most capped players====
{{See also|Scotland Men's International Roll of Honour}}
[[File:Kenny dalglish figurita (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Kenny Dalglish]] scored a joint record 30 goals in a record 102 international appearances]]
[[Kenny Dalglish]] holds the record for Scotland appearances, having played 102 times between 1971 and 1986. He is the only Scotland player to have reached 100 [[cap (sport)|caps]].<ref name = "roll of honour"/> Current player [[Andy Robertson]] is second, having played 94 times since his debut in 2014.<ref name = "roll of honour"/> [[Jim Leighton]] is third, having played 91 times, a Scottish record for appearances by a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]].<ref name = "roll of honour"/> 

