==United Kingdom team==
{{Main|United Kingdom national football team|Great Britain men's Olympic football team}}

Scotland has always participated by itself in most of the major football tournaments, such as the [[FIFA World Cup]] and the [[UEFA European Championship]]. At the [[Olympic Games]] the [[International Olympic Committee]] charter only permit a [[Great Britain men's Olympic football team|Great Britain Olympic football team]], representing the whole of the United Kingdom, to compete.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/may/21/scotland.london|title=Salmond aims for Scottish Olympic gold|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Dan|last=Bell|date=21 May 2007|access-date=4 September 2011|location=London|archive-date=3 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141003135815/http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/may/21/scotland.london|url-status=live}}</ref> Teams of amateur players represented [[Great Britain at the Olympics]] from 1900 until 1972, but the FA stopped entering a team after then because the distinction between amateur and professional was abolished. The [[London 2012 Olympic bid|successful bid]] by London for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] prompted the FA to explore how a team could be entered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/olympics_2012/4657649.stm|title=FA wants GB team in 2012 Olympics|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=6 July 2005|access-date=6 July 2012|archive-date=11 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080911192536/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/olympics_2012/4657649.stm|url-status=live}}</ref> The SFA responded by stating that it would not participate, as it feared that this would threaten the independent status of the Scotland national team.<ref>{{cite web | title=No Scots for GB Olympic football | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4426566.stm | website=BBC Sport | publisher=BBC | date=11 November 2005 | access-date=11 April 2007 | archive-date=8 November 2006 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061108203443/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4426566.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> [[President of FIFA|FIFA President]] [[Sepp Blatter]] denied this,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/4206540.stm | title=Smith 'excited' by Olympic team | website=BBC Sport | publisher=BBC | date=2 September 2005 | access-date=8 January 2008 | archive-date=30 May 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220530134146/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4206540.stm | url-status=live }}</ref> but the SFA expressed concern that a future President could take a different view. An agreement was reached in May 2009 whereby the FA would be permitted to organise a team using only England-qualified players,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/8072981.stm |title=Nations pave way for 2012 GB team |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=29 May 2009 |access-date=5 January 2010 |archive-date=31 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531083536/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/8072981.stm |url-status=live }}</ref> but this was successfully challenged by the [[British Olympic Association]]. Only English and Welsh players were selected for the men's squad,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/football/9369976/London-2012-Olympics-Stuart-Pearce-names-Team-GB-football-squad.html |title=London 2012 Olympics: Stuart Pearce names Team GB football squad |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=2 July 2012 |access-date=17 November 2019 |first=Paul |last=Kelso |archive-date=16 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116184030/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/football/9369976/London-2012-Olympics-Stuart-Pearce-names-Team-GB-football-squad.html |url-status=live }}</ref> but two Scottish players were selected for the [[Great Britain women's Olympic football team|women's team]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/football/9356444/London-2012-Olympics-Hope-Powell-names-first-ever-Team-GB-womens-football-squad-for-Games.html| newspaper=The Daily Telegraph| title=London 2012 Olympics: Hope Powell names first-ever Team GB women's football squad for Games| date=26 June 2012| access-date=26 June 2012| first=Alice| last=Philipson| archive-date=26 June 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626215951/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/football/9356444/London-2012-Olympics-Hope-Powell-names-first-ever-Team-GB-womens-football-squad-for-Games.html| url-status=live}}</ref>

